Description: CVE-2026-29167 - Fix inheritance in per-dir context for uldap_connection_find
 Use-after-free in mod_ldap's uldap_connection_find() when invoked from a
 per-directory configuration context. The previous code used
 apr_array_copy_hdr() to "save away a copy of the client cert list",
 which only copies the array header and leaves the element pointers
 (path, password) referencing memory owned by the per-directory config
 pool. That pool may be reclaimed while the cached LDAP connection
 (allocated in a long-lived connection pool) is still in use, leading
 to a use-after-free that may be triggerable remotely.
 .
 The fix replaces the shallow header copy with a full apr_array_copy()
 and then duplicates each client certificate's path and password into
 the connection's own pool with apr_pstrdup(), severing the dangling
 references.
 .
 Upstream commit 2cf9b3f393633f43746047e779fdf265a1ad8016 on the
 apache/httpd 2.4.x branch (released in 2.4.68); merge of trunk
 r1934932 as r1934935.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/apache/httpd/commit/2cf9b3f393633f43746047e779fdf265a1ad8016
Author: Joe Orton <jorton@apache.org>
Last-Update: 2026-06-15
---
--- a/modules/ldap/util_ldap.c
+++ b/modules/ldap/util_ldap.c
@@ -897,8 +897,23 @@ static util_ldap_connection_t *
          */
         l->secure = secureflag;
 
-        /* save away a copy of the client cert list that is presently valid */
-        l->client_certs = apr_array_copy_hdr(l->pool, dc->client_certs);
+        /* Deep-copy the client cert list into the connection pool so that
+         * the cached connection does not retain pointers into the
+         * (potentially short-lived) per-directory config pool.
+         */
+        l->client_certs = apr_array_copy(l->pool, dc->client_certs);
+        if (!apr_is_empty_array(l->client_certs)) {
+            int i;
+            apr_ldap_opt_tls_cert_t *certs;
+
+            certs = (apr_ldap_opt_tls_cert_t *)l->client_certs->elts;
+            for (i = 0; i < l->client_certs->nelts; i++) {
+                if (certs[i].path)
+                    certs[i].path = apr_pstrdup(l->pool, certs[i].path);
+                if (certs[i].password)
+                    certs[i].password = apr_pstrdup(l->pool, certs[i].password);
+            }
+        }
 
         /* whether or not to keep this connection in the pool when it's returned */
         l->keep = (st->connection_pool_ttl == 0) ? 0 : 1;
Description: CVE-2026-44185 - Fix stack buffer over-read in OCSP send_request()
 In modules/ssl/ssl_util_ocsp.c send_request(), the write-buffer pointer
 was advanced by the originally requested length ("remain") rather than
 the number of bytes actually sent by apr_socket_send() ("wlen"). When a
 partial send occurs (short write), the next loop iteration reads past
 the end of the on-stack request buffer, leading to a buffer over-read
 against an attacker-controlled OCSP responder.
 .
 The fix advances wbuf by wlen (the length actually written) so that
 retransmission of the unsent tail starts at the correct offset.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/apache/httpd/commit/32b7e2e66477020ba75b78ab43fb8890ec292ad2
Bug: https://github.com/apache/httpd/pull/603
Author: Joe Orton <jorton@apache.org>
Last-Update: 2026-06-15

--- a/modules/ssl/ssl_util_ocsp.c
+++ b/modules/ssl/ssl_util_ocsp.c
@@ -133,7 +133,7 @@ static apr_socket_t *send_request(BIO *r
             apr_size_t wlen = remain;

             rv = apr_socket_send(sd, wbuf, &wlen);
-            wbuf += remain;
+            wbuf += wlen;
             remain -= wlen;
         } while (rv == APR_SUCCESS && remain > 0);

Description: CVE-2026-34356 - ap_proxy_cookie_reverse_map: fix dup path/domain
 Heap-based buffer overflow in mod_proxy's ap_proxy_cookie_reverse_map() when
 handling Set-Cookie headers from a backend that contain duplicate path= or
 domain= attributes. A malicious or compromised backend can trigger memory
 corruption / availability impact in front-end Apache servers configured with
 ProxyPassReverseCookieDomain or ProxyPassReverseCookiePath.
 .
 Per RFC 6265 §5.3 (4) and (7), only the last domain= / path= attribute in a
 Set-Cookie header should be meaningful. This patch resets newpath/pdiff and
 newdomain/ddiff each time a fresh path=/domain= token is detected so that the
 final reverse-map computation uses sizes consistent with the offsets of the
 last occurrence, preventing the out-of-bounds write.
 .
 Affects Apache HTTP Server 2.4.0 through 2.4.67; fixed in 2.4.68.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/apache/httpd/commit/403269396d24404e2576a9b20f96cd0b10574048
Author: Eric Covener <covener@apache.org>
Last-Update: 2026-06-15
---
--- a/modules/proxy/proxy_util.c
+++ b/modules/proxy/proxy_util.c
@@ -1036,6 +1036,12 @@ PROXY_DECLARE(const char *) ap_proxy_cookie_reverse_map(request_rec *r,
             poffs = pathp - tmpstr_orig;
             l1 = strlen(pathp);
             pathe = str + poffs + l1;
+            /*
+             * RFC 6265 § 5.3 7): Only the last path= should be meaningful
+             * so reset anything previously found.
+             */
+            newpath = NULL;
+            pdiff = 0;
             if (conf->interpolate_env == 1) {
                 ent = (struct proxy_alias *)rconf->cookie_paths->elts;
             }
@@ -1056,6 +1062,12 @@ PROXY_DECLARE(const char *) ap_proxy_cookie_reverse_map(request_rec *r,
             doffs = domainp - tmpstr_orig;
             l1 = strlen(domainp);
             domaine = str + doffs + l1;
+            /*
+             * RFC 6265 § 5.3 4): Only the last domain= should be meaningful
+             * so reset anything previously found.
+             */
+            newdomain = NULL;
+            ddiff = 0;
             if (conf->interpolate_env == 1) {
                 ent = (struct proxy_alias *)rconf->cookie_domains->elts;
             }
Description: Fix CVE-2026-44186 infinite loop in mod_proxy_ftp Retry-After parsing
 The proxy_ftp_handler function in modules/proxy/mod_proxy_ftp.c contains a
 while loop that scans FTP server messages for a Retry-After value. The loop
 pointer (secs_str) was never advanced when the digit/whitespace condition
 was not met, resulting in an infinite loop / denial of service that could
 be triggered by an attacker-controlled backend FTP server.
 .
 This patch adds the missing secs_str++ increment (and braces around the
 loop body) so that the parser advances correctly and terminates.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/apache/httpd/commit/414de374a06549b2c6710cbcff81c3821379f75c
Author: Eric Covener <covener@apache.org>
Last-Update: 2026-06-15

--- a/modules/proxy/mod_proxy_ftp.c
+++ b/modules/proxy/mod_proxy_ftp.c
@@ -1206,10 +1206,12 @@ static int proxy_ftp_handler(request_rec *r, proxy_worker *worker,
         time_t secs;
 
         /* Look for a number, preceded by whitespace */
-        while (*secs_str)
+        while (*secs_str) {
             if ((secs_str==ftpmessage || apr_isspace(secs_str[-1])) &&
                 apr_isdigit(secs_str[0]))
                 break;
+            secs_str++;
+        }
         if (*secs_str != '\0') {
             secs = atol(secs_str);
             apr_table_addn(r->headers_out, "Retry-After",
Description: CVE-2026-42536 - Fix accounting in mod_xml2enc fix_skipto
 In modules/filters/mod_xml2enc.c, the fix_skipto() function adjusted
 ctx->bytes when stripping content preceding a recognised start element
 but failed to also decrement ctx->bblen (the brigade buffer length).
 This accounting mismatch between bytes and bblen could lead to incorrect
 buffer length tracking in subsequent processing of the input brigade.
 .
 This patch decrements ctx->bblen by the same amount as ctx->bytes when
 the leading bytes are removed from the buffer, keeping the two values
 in sync.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/apache/httpd/commit/cb1f79c0ce66393c48657b19df754f16b79af543
Author: Joe Orton <jorton@apache.org>
Last-Update: 2026-06-15
---
--- a/modules/filters/mod_xml2enc.c
+++ b/modules/filters/mod_xml2enc.c
@@ -164,6 +164,7 @@ static void fix_skipto(request_rec* r, xml2ctx* ctx)
                         apr_bucket_delete(b);
                     }
                     ctx->bytes -= (p-ctx->buf);
+                    ctx->bblen -= (p-ctx->buf);
                     ctx->buf = p ;
                     found = 1;
                     ap_log_rerror(APLOG_MARK, APLOG_DEBUG, 0, r, APLOGNO(01428)
Description: CVE-2026-48913 - mod_http2 use-after-free in c2_setup_io on file handle exhaustion
 When apr_file_pipe_create_pools() fails (e.g. file descriptor exhaustion),
 the beam send/received/consumed callbacks were already registered and
 referenced c2/stream state that becomes invalid, leading to use-after-free.
 Move the callback registrations to after pipe creation succeeds.
 .
 The upstream mod_h2 v2.0.39->2.0.42 bundle also carries CVE-2026-49975
 (h2_util.c cookie accounting) and TLS buffering refactors in h2_c1_io.c.
 Debian bookworm 2.4.67-1~deb12u3 already ships the CVE-2026-49975 fix via
 debian/patches/CVE-2026-49975_*.patch, so only the c2_setup_io reorder
 from this release is backported here.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/apache/httpd/commit/dbf1cc4dd62b681a0066271720994a047a3329ca
Bug: https://github.com/icing/mod_h2/pull/323
Author: Stefan Eissing <icing@apache.org>
Last-Update: 2026-06-19
